Module 1 Deep Dive: The C++ Firehose Implementation
1. Ultra-Fast Parsing with simdjson
Standard JSON parsers (like Python's json or C++ nlohmann/json) are too slow for tick-by-tick firehoses. We use simdjson, which uses SIMD instructions to parse gigabytes of JSON per second.

The Implementation Logic:

C++
// src/ingestion/parser.cpp
#include "simdjson.h"

void process_shoonya_tick(std::string_view json_payload) {
    simdjson::ondemand::parser parser;
    auto doc = parser.iterate(json_payload);
    
    // Extracting fields using high-speed pointer arithmetic
    std::string_view symbol = doc["tk"];
    double last_price = doc["lp"];
    int64_t volume = doc["v"];
    
    // Map to Protobuf and send to IPC
    Karthik::Tick tick;
    tick.set_symbol(symbol.data());
    tick.set_ltp(last_price);
    // ... further serialization
}
2. Unix Domain Sockets (UDS) for Local IPC
TCP/IP (even on localhost) introduces unnecessary overhead. For the "M1 to M2" bridge, we use UDS.

Performance: ~40 microseconds latency vs. ~150-200 microseconds for TCP.

Reliability: No packet loss; kernel-level flow control ensures data integrity.

3. The Protobuf Schema (core/messages.proto)
This is the "Source of Truth" for all data moving through the 8 modules.

Protocol Buffers
syntax = "proto3";

message Tick {
    string sym = 1;     // Symbol
    fixed64 ts = 2;     // Nanosecond Timestamp
    float ltp = 3;      // Last Traded Price
    uint64 vol = 4;     // Volume
    float bid = 5;      // Best Bid
    float ask = 6;      // Best Ask
}
4. Error Handling: The "Circuit Breaker"
If the Gateway receives 3 consecutive malformed packets or a "429 Rate Limit" from the broker, it initiates an Exponential Backoff.

State Protection: Before shutting down, it writes the last_sequence_id to Redis so the Order Reconciler (Module 7) can audit any pending fills during the downtime.

